It’s long, but please stay with me…

A bit more context on the issue with the Telus configuration (hard-coded IP address ranges vs. dns entry)

We do not own the uwfl.tc3-gwl.telus.com DNS entry and cannot alter what it resolves to internally (at least legally I think), so the best we can do is ensure whatever IP address it resolves to is allowed within our firewall/routing rules to allow the traffic to connect from Azure à WDC à MPLS à Telus data centre.

The uwfl.tc3-gwl.telus.com dns entry resolves to this presently:

C:\Users\LL59670 > nslookup uwfl.tc3-gwl.telus.com

Server:  gwdsp0.gwl.bz

Address:  156.11.98.121

Non-authoritative answer:

DNS request timed out.

timeout was 2 seconds.

Name:    uwfl.tc3-gwl.telus.com

Address:  100.77.84.46

I believe what Telus is asking us to do is to use the DNS entry to determine the correct IP address to connect to from within the ADF linked service as they will switch the primary IP around for maintenance, failovers, upgrades, etc.. Telus did this in the past (moved from .84 to .85) and our ingestions failed because we were using a specific IP address instead of a DNS entry which is normally what we use in our other ADF linked services.

The following Class C IP ranges (as defined by Telus) is part of our routing rules for CDP 1.0. This route table is applied to the subnet where the Self-Hosted Integration Runtimes are located as the traffic is being moved through them:

The same Class C IP ranges are defined for the Transient DLZ in CDP 2.0 production with its own SHIR subnet:

In short, we are hedging our bets on what the DNS entry will resolve to (IP address-wise) and allowing traffic for it through our networks.

Now, the issue comes into play with the ADF linked service definition. Here is what is in place that works presently:

If we change the server name to a DNS entry instead of a hard-coded IP address, the connection fails due to a timeout:

The only difference I see is on the fourth octet of address. The hard-coded IP is 100.77.84. 12 and the dns entry resolves to 100.77.84. 46 presently. Given the above route table entries, I would think this traffic enabled but perhaps the f/w rules are more specific once we enter WDC routing. I did a tracert from one of the Self-Hosted Integration Runtime (SHIR) VMs that ADF uses to get the data from telus and the routes (at least from Azure) appear to be ending up in the same place:

It may be possible that I can’t trace the traffic once it goes internal to WDC to account for the timeouts above.

I also tried using the IP address that the DNS entry resolves to presently (100.77.84.46), and that failed so this isn’t an issue with ADF not being able to handle the dns entry (as we use it in every other connection we do):

Shelli,

Can you please confirm that we should be able to connect to Telus using 100.77.84.46 presently as well as 100.77.84.12? If we rule out DNS and just use IP addresses for now, it would seem that Telus is telling us this should work. Can you make sure they are not restricting connectivity to a single IP address on their side? I haven’t received any response from Telus indicating that anything but 100.77.84.12 is open on their side.
